<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="284" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/1567:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-08">August 8,
                                    1943</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4815. My Greek colleague<note n="1" xml:id="d284fn1">Spyro
                                    Marchetti.</note> tells me that the Papal Nuncio<note n="2" xml:id="d284fn2">Filippo Bernardini.</note> called upon him and
                                asked him to pass on to me and to my British colleague<note n="3" xml:id="d284fn3">Clifford John Norton.</note> the following as
                                coming from an Italian source here without revealing <pb facs="0686" n="572" xml:id="pg_572"/> his name: the Badoglio Government is
                                prepared to accept immediately armistice on “honorable terms”
                                provided Italy is not occupied. This only way for <gloss target="#t_B1">B</gloss> to get Germans out. If Germans refuse
                                    <gloss target="#t_B1">B</gloss> will ask Allied assistance.</p>
                            <p>My Greek colleague suggests action of Nuncio may well have been
                                inspired by the Vatican. Am inclined believe <hi rend="italic">Nonce</hi> acted on his own initiative.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>